<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910301-0034</DOCNO><DOCID>910301-0034.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   New York Daily News Sets   Talks on Sale to Maxwell</HL><DATE>03/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   TRB LABOR U.MXC</CO><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- The New York Daily News said it will openformal talks regarding the sale of the paper to British mediaowner Robert Maxwell after the collapse last night ofnegotiations between management and the striking unions.   Talks ended as the private mediator, former U.S. LaborSecretary William J. Usery, backed out of the negotiations,saying there was not enough time to continue bargaining.Tribune Co.'s Daily News had set Monday as a deadline forunion concessions, after which a date to shut down the paperwould be set.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Usery said he was stepping out to clear the way for a&quot;qualified purchaser,&quot; should there be one.   Lazard Freres andamp; Co., which was retained to screenpotential bidders, said Mr. Maxwell's representatives wouldmeet soon with Daily News management. Lazard Freres didn'trule out that other candidates might also surface.   But Lazard general partner Steve Rattner said prospectivebuyer Mortimer Zuckerman, a publisher and real estatedeveloper, &quot;is out of the picture permanently.&quot; Mr. Rattnersaid, &quot;We could not reach a meeting of the minds on financialterms.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>